SIT (Tajfel, 1979)

-   A person has not just one "personal self, but rather several social selves that correspond to group membership.
-   We categorize ourselves in terms of group membership
-   People can boost self esteem through both personal achievement and through affiliation with groups

Psychological Mechanisms

1.  Social Categorization
2.  Social comparison
3.  Tendency to use group membership as a source of self-esteem

Categorization

-   Individuals strive to maintain a positive self-concept as well as a positive social identity
-   People make comparisons between in-group and outgroup on valued dimensions to establish maintain and defined positive in group distinctiveness
-   When a social comparison results in a positive outcome for the in-group, the need for a positive social identity is satisfied but the opposite may also happen 
-   Intergroup discrimination can be one way to uphold a positive social identity for the in group

Strengths

-   SIT assumes that intergroup conflict is not required for discrimination to occur. This is supported by empirical research
-   SIT can explain some of the mechanisms involved in establishing "positive distinctiveness" to the ingroup by maximising differences to the outgroup
-   SIT has been applied to understanding behaviours such as ethnocentrism, ingroup favouritism, conformity to ingroup norms and stereotyping.

Limitations

-   Minimal group research has been criticised for artificiality. The experimental setup is so far from natural behaviour that it can be questioned whether it reflects how people would react in real world
